man: Two questions--
one for the audience, actually.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:04.834
Who would consider themselves
a pair programmer?

00:43:06.767 --> 00:43:08.567
Fitzpatrick: See, they can't get
their hands all the way up.

00:43:08.567 --> 00:43:10.567
[laughter]

00:43:10.567 --> 00:43:13.400
man: And the same question
to you guys, really.

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:14.901
What do you think
about pair programming,

00:43:14.901 --> 00:43:16.400
kind of formally?

00:43:16.400 --> 00:43:19.067
Fitzpatrick:
I personally think it's ideal

00:43:19.067 --> 00:43:20.901
if you're working
on something really difficult.

00:43:20.901 --> 00:43:22.901
When I wrote CVS to SVN,

00:43:22.901 --> 00:43:24.567
which is probably
one of the hardest things

00:43:24.567 --> 00:43:26.067
I've ever worked on
in my life--

00:43:26.067 --> 00:43:30.734
I learned more about CVS and RCS
than I wanted to learn ever.

00:43:30.734 --> 00:43:32.400
Karl Fogel and I did a lot
of pair programming.

00:43:32.400 --> 00:43:33.767
It was really good,

00:43:33.767 --> 00:43:35.734
because it was really grungy,
difficult problems.

00:43:35.734 --> 00:43:37.067
But for sort of day to day,

00:43:37.067 --> 00:43:40.434
I prefer more of
the write-code-review process.

00:43:40.434 --> 00:43:42.834
Collins-Sussman: It creates
social stress, right?

00:43:42.834 --> 00:43:44.334
If you're pair-programming
with somebody,

00:43:44.334 --> 00:43:46.901
you better be really--
know each other really well

00:43:46.901 --> 00:43:49.567
and be very tolerant
of each other's quirks, right?

00:43:49.567 --> 00:43:52.234
Otherwise, it can actually--
you can start arguing

00:43:52.234 --> 00:43:54.734
about whoever's driving, right?

00:43:54.734 --> 00:43:56.234
"Don't format
the code that way."

00:43:56.234 --> 00:43:57.901
Or, "Don't you know
that shortcut?"

00:43:57.901 --> 00:43:59.734
Or, you know, it can get
a little maddening.

00:43:59.734 --> 00:44:01.734
Fitzpatrick: There's a number of
really good engineers at Google

00:44:01.734 --> 00:44:04.234
who pair-program all the time,
and they do a great job of it,

00:44:04.234 --> 00:44:06.567
and they're
amazingly productive.

00:44:06.567 --> 00:44:08.400
man: Thanks.
Fitzpatrick: Yeah.

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:10.667
man: So advice on dealing
with egos,

00:44:10.667 --> 00:44:12.133
'cause I agree with you guys,

00:44:12.133 --> 00:44:13.934
but there's definitely people
on the team

00:44:13.934 --> 00:44:16.234
that, you know, their ego
is always in the way.

00:44:16.234 --> 00:44:17.734
Fitzpatrick:
Advice on dealing with egos.

00:44:17.734 --> 00:44:19.234
Collins-Sussman:
What is the advice?

00:44:19.234 --> 00:44:21.534
Fitzpatrick: How do you deal
with people that have a big ego?

00:44:21.534 --> 00:44:23.734
Is that the question?
Wow.

00:44:23.734 --> 00:44:25.234
Um...pass.

00:44:25.234 --> 00:44:26.901
No, I'm kidding.
[laughter]

00:44:26.901 --> 00:44:29.901
That's a hard question,
because...

00:44:29.901 --> 00:44:32.901
typically if they're running
the project, they'll--

00:44:32.901 --> 00:44:34.901
Again,
like attracts like, okay?

00:44:34.901 --> 00:44:38.400
People who are sort of
the friendlier, nicer,

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:39.667
consensus-building people

00:44:39.667 --> 00:44:41.734
are gonna attract people
that like to work with that.

00:44:41.734 --> 00:44:43.400
People who are the big,
you know, ego--

00:44:43.400 --> 00:44:46.234
"It's about me.
Let's be aggressive here.

00:44:46.234 --> 00:44:48.400
I'm the alpha male.
Let's fight about things."

00:44:48.400 --> 00:44:49.868
Collins-Sussman:
They attract other alphas.

00:44:49.868 --> 00:44:51.133
Fitzpatrick: Exactly. They're
gonna attract other people

00:44:51.133 --> 00:44:52.400
that either want to follow them
and be like,

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:53.734
"Oh, yes, you're right.
Wonderful."

00:44:53.734 --> 00:44:54.901
Or they're people
that just want to fight them,

00:44:54.901 --> 00:44:56.267
because that's
what they want to do.

00:44:56.267 --> 00:44:58.234
So I don't know
I'd have a particular recipe--

