00:49:13.767 --> 00:49:16.067
If I were truly bored
at my job, right?

00:49:16.067 --> 00:49:18.067
Fitzpatrick: Right.
In the Open Source world,

00:49:18.067 --> 00:49:19.901
you know,
you typically want to attract

00:49:19.901 --> 00:49:21.400
these kind of people
and projects.

00:49:21.400 --> 00:49:24.234
So if you're--
If it's built on consensus

00:49:24.234 --> 00:49:27.234
and other people can still
come in and have an influence,

00:49:27.234 --> 00:49:30.567
that's typically what
will attract the bigger fish.

00:49:30.567 --> 00:49:32.901
man: So you're saying
if you can change

00:49:32.901 --> 00:49:34.834
your corporate environment,

00:49:34.834 --> 00:49:37.234
start an Open Source project,
basically.

00:49:37.234 --> 00:49:40.234
Fitzpatrick:
Again, corporate environments--

00:49:40.234 --> 00:49:41.567
it's really risky.

00:49:41.567 --> 00:49:43.067
If you are one
of the small fish

00:49:43.067 --> 00:49:45.901
or, like, you're just
an engineer on a large project,

00:49:45.901 --> 00:49:48.400
you know, you have no power
to change that necessarily.

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:49.701
You can do what you do,

00:49:49.701 --> 00:49:51.734
but you're not gonna be able
