00:49:51.734 --> 00:49:53.234
from that seat that you're in.

00:49:53.234 --> 00:49:55.234
Collins-Sussman: If you're
a big fish in a corporation,

00:49:55.234 --> 00:49:56.567
you probably do have
a lot of power

00:49:56.567 --> 00:49:59.067
to start migrating your career

00:49:59.067 --> 00:50:01.567
towards other
bigger fish, right?

00:50:01.567 --> 00:50:03.234
Fitzpatrick: Right.
Collins-Sussman: It's possible.

00:50:03.234 --> 00:50:06.400
Fitzpatrick:
Next question, please.

00:50:06.400 --> 00:50:10.234
man: Hi. You talked
about avoiding a low bus factor

00:50:10.234 --> 00:50:11.901
and having as many people look

00:50:11.901 --> 00:50:13.734
at as many pieces of code
as possible.

00:50:13.734 --> 00:50:15.167
And you talked about it
in the context

00:50:15.167 --> 00:50:17.567
of people being egotistical and
wanting to own a piece of code

00:50:17.567 --> 00:50:19.067
and no one else touch it.

00:50:19.067 --> 00:50:20.767
But I think there's
a practical factor there.

00:50:20.767 --> 00:50:22.234
When you have a big project
with few people,

00:50:22.234 --> 00:50:24.400
that the more proficient
someone is with a component,

00:50:24.400 --> 00:50:26.067
the more quickly
they can implement features

00:50:26.067 --> 00:50:27.400
or solve bugs.

00:50:27.400 --> 00:50:30.734
And if everyone spreads
themselves too thin, maybe...

00:50:30.734 --> 00:50:32.400
maybe development
would slow down.

00:50:32.400 --> 00:50:33.434
I don't know.

00:50:33.434 --> 00:50:35.234
I feel like this is true
on my project

00:50:35.234 --> 00:50:36.901
and my work experience.

00:50:36.901 --> 00:50:38.567
I feel like when bugs come in,
we want to assign it

00:50:38.567 --> 00:50:40.067
to the person who knows
that component best.

00:50:40.067 --> 00:50:41.567
They can fix it fastest.

00:50:41.567 --> 00:50:43.901
But we've thought about maybe
purposely assigning bugs

00:50:43.901 --> 00:50:46.400
to people who know it less
to help spread knowledge.

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:48.901
Is that a good idea, or is this
concern completely false

00:50:48.901 --> 00:50:50.234
and just coming out of ego?

00:50:50.234 --> 00:50:51.734
Collins-Sussman: I think
there's a tension there,

00:50:51.734 --> 00:50:52.734
like you said, right?

00:50:52.734 --> 00:50:54.601
The fastest thing to do

00:50:54.601 --> 00:50:58.400
is to have the people who know
the code best work on it, right?

00:50:58.400 --> 00:51:01.167
But you need to sort of find
a balance, right?

00:51:01.167 --> 00:51:03.734
Where you're balancing
short term versus long term.

00:51:03.734 --> 00:51:05.234
In the short term,

00:51:05.234 --> 00:51:07.234
it's best to have the experts
work on the code they know,

00:51:07.234 --> 00:51:08.901
'cause it'll get done
faster, right?

00:51:08.901 --> 00:51:11.400
In the long term, though,
you want to occasionally,

00:51:11.400 --> 00:51:13.400
like you said,
maybe have someone

00:51:13.400 --> 00:51:15.901
who doesn't know
that code as well

00:51:15.901 --> 00:51:18.734
pair-program a bug fix
with somebody who does,

00:51:18.734 --> 00:51:22.567
or give somebody a small task
in that foreign area of code,

00:51:22.567 --> 00:51:24.567
which isn't particularly
time-critical,

00:51:24.567 --> 00:51:27.434
but will give that person
some experience with the code

00:51:27.434 --> 00:51:29.400
so that if the expert
does get hit by a bus,

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:30.901
you'll be covered
for the long term.

00:51:30.901 --> 00:51:32.501
So, yeah, it's
about risk management, right?

00:51:32.501 --> 00:51:33.734
Short and long term.

00:51:33.734 --> 00:51:35.234
Fitzpatrick: And we're certainly
not advocating

00:51:35.234 --> 00:51:36.601
that everyone on your project

00:51:36.601 --> 00:51:38.734
knows how to do absolutely
everything in the code base.

00:51:38.734 --> 00:51:41.400
There's ways
of improving your bus factor

00:51:41.400 --> 00:51:44.734
without actually making everyone
into a generalist,

00:51:44.734 --> 00:51:47.067
and that is
good solid documentation

00:51:47.067 --> 00:51:49.234
in code and comments,
design docs,

00:51:49.234 --> 00:51:51.067
and then just
general documentation.

00:51:51.067 --> 00:51:52.567
Collins-Sussman:
And code review, right?

00:51:52.567 --> 00:51:55.067
If one person--If there's code
review going on,

00:51:55.067 --> 00:51:57.567
then it's really pretty much
impossible for one person

00:51:57.567 --> 00:51:58.901
to know an area of code.

00:51:58.901 --> 00:52:01.067
Somebody
must've reviewed that code

00:52:01.067 --> 00:52:02.400
that went in there, right?

00:52:02.400 --> 00:52:03.901
At least have
a cursory knowledge.

00:52:03.901 --> 00:52:05.734
Fitzpatrick:
Next question, please,

00:52:05.734 --> 00:52:07.067
